Increase the Army's End Strength.
In this option, the active Army would grow by 80,000 personnel--enough, CBO estimates, to provide the service with another heavy division, one more light division, and 19,000 additional support personnel.21 CBO assumed that the additional support units created would be largely military police, civil affairs, and psychological-operations units.
Those types of support personnel have been in high demand in peacekeeping operations over the past decade and are concentrated in the Army's reserve component.
Thus, creating additional active units of those types could reduce the levels of mobilization and deployment needed for reserve personnel.
If the Army's end strength (the level at which DoD is authorized to recruit and maintain the service) was expanded by 80,000 personnel, the size of the occupation that could be sustained in Iraq over the long term would increase by 18,000 to 23,000 military personnel--equivalent to another 1b to 2 combat brigades.
