That estimate assumes that seven civilians would replace every 10 military personnel.
That ratio is consistent with DoD's experience in outsourcing competitions.
CBO assumed that in this case, the new civilians would be organized in the most efficient manner, similar to what would occur in an outsourcing competition.
Although the 65,000 personnel positions that would be freed up by this option are less than the 80,000 associated with the previous option, these positions would be sufficient to create almost the same mix of units because additional civilians--rather than military personnel--would be hired to perform administrative functions.
