If higher or lower deployment levels are deemed acceptable, then lower or higher rotation ratios, respectively (or rotation bases, as they are often called), will be required.
For example, deployment levels that required soldiers or Marines to be away from home for all but 30 days of leave per year (335 days, or 92 percent of the time) would require a small rotation base: only slightly more than 1.
However, such a high level of deployment--roughly equal to three-quarters of the deployable force, and much higher than the current level of active Army forces deployed worldwide--would be hard to sustain for a long period.
Conversely, if the need for both individual and collective training, as well as preparation and recovery, 36
